Diseases of globalization
Globalization is being tested as never before.
Its tensions are roaring everywhere.
The majority of sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk another recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in only a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Some regions of the world have reaped great benefits from globalization, notably East Asia and China in recent years.
However, some regions have gained only meager benefits, particularly sub-Saharan Africa.
The U.S. government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they face.
The slow growth in Africa, assert American leaders, is caused by the incompetence of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced declining living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that were among the last in international comparisons of government performance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow faster than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are exceptions).
Coastal countries tend to perform better than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to perform better than countries that are far from the main markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If rich countries do not care much about these structural problems, the gap between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If rich countries shift the blame onto unlucky countries by claiming that they are somehow culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify the unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than what rich countries, and particularly the United States, offer.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely addressing the basic needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their own country.
But in others, an honest look at the evidence gathered will reveal that the main causes of poverty relate to diseases, climate instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest assessment would also indicate that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds on their own to resolve such problems.
Instead of seeing rich countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
An example will strikingly illustrate this situation.
Disease control requires a health system capable of providing survival medicines and basic preventive services such as bed nets to fight malaria and vitamins to combat nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This amount is just a drop in the bucket for rich countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the means of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of only $200 per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even though Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases unless it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of blaming the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that are holding back their growth and economic development.
In some regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and Internet connectivity to help these remote regions create productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to funding these projects.
In sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges relate to disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems concern water scarcity, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent in globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all consensus of Washington is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinkers of the rich and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our shared future depends on it.
